# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: smart-contracts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] A **decentralized autonomous organization** (**DAO**) is a software system for organization of other computer programs handled through a decentralized ledger technology like a blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] These systems are used most commonly to handle voting and finances, among other processes.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] The precise legal status of this type of organization system is unclear.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] DAOs are closely associated with cryptocurrency and Web3.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] The name and concept originated with the 2016 launch of The DAO, a system built to manage an Ethereum-based venture capital fund amassing 3.6 million in ether cryptocurrency, then worth more than US$70 million.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] This system was later hacked and drained of US$50 million weeks later.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] The hack was reversed in the following weeks, and the money restored, via a hard fork of the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Most Ethereum miners and clients switched to the new fork while the original chain became Ethereum Classic.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] The governance of DAOs is subject to controversy.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] As these often allocate and distribute tokens that grant voting rights, their accumulation may lead to concentration of power.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Although the term may be traced back to the 1990s, it was not until 2013 that it became more widely adopted.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Although some argue that Bitcoin was the first DAO, the term is often understood today as software & smart contracts on top of an existing blockchain network.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] This approach eliminates the need to involve a mutually acceptable trusted third party in any decentralized digital interaction or cryptocurrency transaction.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] The costs of a blockchain-enabled transaction and of the associated data reporting may be substantially offset by the elimination of both the trusted third party and of the need for repetitive recording of contract exchanges in different records.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] For example, the blockchain data could, in principle and if regulatory structures permit it, replace public documents such as deeds and titles.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] In theory, a blockchain approach allows multiple cloud computing users to enter a loosely coupled peer-to-peer smart contract collaboration.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Vitalik Buterin proposed that after a DAO is launched, it might be organized to run without human managerial interactivity, provided the smart contracts are supported by a Turing-complete platform.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Ethereum, built on a blockchain and launched in 2015, has been described as meeting that Turing threshold, thus enabling such DAOs.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Decentralized autonomous organizations can facilitate open platforms through which individuals control their identities and their personal data.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] DAO governance is coordinated using tokens or NFTs that grant voting powers.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Governance is conducted through a series of proposals that voting addresses vote on through the blockchain, and the possession of more governance tokens often translates to greater voting power.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Inactive holders of governance tokens can be a major obstacle for DAO governance, which has led to implementations allowing voting power to be delegated to other parties.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Tokens that grant voting powers are often not used to vote.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Inactive or non-voting addresses in DAOs often disrupt the organization's possible functionality.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Another risk is the concentration of power in the case that individual addresses accumulate large amounts of tokens that grant voting power.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Concentration of these tokens may defeat ambitions to distribute governance power.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] In a study of a selected number of decentralized finance DAOs, the distribution of tokens was shown to be highly concentrated among a small number of addresses in the sample.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] The precise legal status of this type of business organization is generally unclear, and may vary by jurisdiction.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] On 1 July 2021, Wyoming became the first US state to recognize DAOs as a legal entity.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] American CryptoFed DAO became the first business entity so recognized.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Some previous approaches to blockchain based companies have been regarded by the U.S.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Securities and Exchange Commission as illegal offers of unregistered securities.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Although often of uncertain legal standing, a DAO may functionally be a corporation without legal status as a corporation: a general partnership.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Known participants, or those at the interface between a DAO and regulated financial systems, may be targets of regulatory enforcement or civil actions if they are out of compliance with the law.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] A DAO's code is difficult to alter once the system is up and running, including bug fixes that would be otherwise trivial in centralized code.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Corrections to a DAO require writing new code and agreement to migrate all the funds.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Although the code is visible to all, it is hard to repair, thus leaving known security holes open to exploitation unless a moratorium is called to enable bug fixing.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] In 2016, a specific DAO, "The DAO", set a record for the largest crowdfunding campaign to date.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Researchers pointed out multiple problems with The DAO's code.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] The DAO's operational procedure allowed investors to withdraw at will any money that had not yet been committed to a project; the funds could thus deplete quickly.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] Although safeguards aimed to prevent gaming shareholders' votes to win investments, there were a "number of security vulnerabilities".
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] These enabled an attempted large withdrawal of funds from The DAO to be initiated in mid-June 2016.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] On 20 July 2016, the Ethereum blockchain was forked to bail out the original contract.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] DAOs can be subject to coups or hostile takeovers that upend its voting structures especially if the voting power is based upon the number of tokens one owns.
[src:smart-contracts/decentralized-autonomous-organization] An example of this occurred in 2022, when one individual collected enough tokens to give themselves voting control over Build Finance DAO, which they then used to drain the DAO of all its cryptocurrency.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] A decentralized application (dapp) is an application built on a decentralized network that combines a smart contract and a frontend user interface.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] On Ethereum, smart contracts are accessible and transparent – like open APIs – so your dapp can even include a smart contract that someone else has written.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] Before learning about dapps, you should cover the blockchain basics and read about the Ethereum network and how it's decentralized.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] A dapp has its backend code running on a decentralized peer-to-peer network.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] Contrast this with an app where the backend code is running on centralized servers.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] A dapp can have frontend code and user interfaces written in any language (just like an app) to make calls to its backend.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] Furthermore, its frontend can get hosted on decentralized storage such as IPFS (opens in a new tab).
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] To introduce dapps, we need to introduce smart contracts – a dapp's backend for lack of a better term.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] For a detailed overview, head to our section on smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] A smart contract is code that lives on the Ethereum blockchain and runs exactly as programmed.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] Once smart contracts are deployed on the network you can't change them.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] Dapps can be decentralized because they are controlled by the logic written into the contract, not an individual or company.
[src:smart-contracts/developers-dapps] This also means you need to design your contracts very carefully and test them thoroughly.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] A "smart contract" is simply a program that runs on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] It's a collection of code (its functions) and data (its state) that resides at a specific address on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Smart contracts are a type of Ethereum account.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] This means they have a balance and can be the target of transactions.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] However they're not controlled by a user, instead they are deployed to the network and run as programmed.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] User accounts can then interact with a smart contract by submitting transactions that execute a function defined on the smart contract.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Smart contracts can define rules, like a regular contract, and automatically enforce them via the code.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Smart contracts cannot be deleted by default, and interactions with them are irreversible.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] If you're just getting started or looking for a less technical introduction, we recommend our introduction to smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Make sure you've read up on accounts, transactions and the Ethereum virtual machine before jumping into the world of smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Perhaps the best metaphor for a smart contract is a vending machine, as described by Nick Szabo (opens in a new tab).
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] With the right inputs, a certain output is guaranteed.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] This logic is programmed into the vending machine.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] A smart contract, like a vending machine, has logic programmed into it.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Like how a vending machine removes the need for a vendor employee, smart contracts can replace intermediaries in many industries.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Anyone can write a smart contract and deploy it to the network.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] You just need to learn how to code in a smart contract language, and have enough ETH to deploy your contract.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Deploying a smart contract is technically a transaction, so you need to pay gas in the same way you need to pay gas for a simple ETH transfer.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] However, gas costs for contract deployment are far higher.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] However, they must be compiled before they can be deployed so that Ethereum's virtual machine can interpret and store the contract.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Smart contracts are public on Ethereum and can be thought of as open APIs.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] This means you can call other smart contracts in your own smart contract to greatly extend what's possible.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Contracts can even deploy other contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Learn more about smart contract composability.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Smart contracts alone cannot get information about "real-world" events because they can't retrieve data from offchain sources.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] This means they can't respond to events in the real world.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Relying on external information could jeopardise consensus, which is important for security and decentralization.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] However, it is important for blockchain applications to be able to use offchain data.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] The solution is oracles which are tools that ingest offchain data and make it available to smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Another limitation of smart contracts is the maximum contract size.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] A smart contract can be a maximum of 24KB or it will run out of gas.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] This can be circumnavigated by using The Diamond Pattern (opens in a new tab).
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Multisig (multiple-signature) contracts are smart contract accounts that require multiple valid signatures to execute a transaction.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] This is very useful for avoiding single points of failure for contracts holding substantial amounts of ether or other tokens.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Multisigs also divide responsibility for contract execution and key management between multiple parties and prevent the loss of a single private key leading to irreversible loss of funds.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] For these reasons, multisig contracts can be used for simple DAO governance.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] Multisigs require N signatures out of M possible acceptable signatures (where N ≤ M, and M > 1) in order to execute.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] A 4/7 multisig requires four out of seven possible valid signatures.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] This means the funds are still retrievable even if three signatures are lost.
[src:smart-contracts/smart-contracts] In this case, it also means that the majority of key-holders must agree and sign in order for the contract to execute.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity was proposed in August 2014 by Gavin Wood The language was later developed by the Ethereum project's Solidity team, led by Christian Reitwiessner.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity is the primary language used to develop smart contracts for Ethereum and other private blockchains, such as the enterprise-oriented Hyperledger Fabric blockchain.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] SWIFT deployed a proof of concept using Solidity running on Hyperledger Fabric.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity is a statically typed programming language designed for developing smart contracts that run on the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) or compatible virtual machines.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity uses ECMAScript-like syntax which makes it familiar for web developers; however unlike ECMAScript it has static typing and variadic return types.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity is different from other EVM-targeting languages such as Serpent and Mutan in some important ways.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] It supports complex member variables for smart contracts, including arbitrarily hierarchical mappings and structs.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity smart contract support inheritance, including multiple inheritance with C3 linearization.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity introduces an application binary interface (ABI) that facilitates multiple type-safe functions within one smart contract (this was also later supported by Serpent).
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] The Solidity proposal also includes "Natural Language Specification", a documentation system for specifying user-centric descriptions of the ramifications of method-calls.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Many security properties of smart contracts are inherently difficult to reason about directly, and the Turing-completeness of Solidity means that verification of arbitrary properties cannot be decidably automated.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Current automated solutions for smart contract security analysis can miss critical violations, produce false positives, and fail to achieve sufficient code coverage on realistic contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] Solidity has been blamed for the error-prone implementation of Ethereum smart contracts due to its counterintuitive nature, its lack of constructs to deal with blockchain domain-specific aspects, and its lack of centralized documentation of known vulnerabilities.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] In 2016, a Cornell University researcher stated that Solidity was partly to blame for The DAO hack that occurred that year.
[src:smart-contracts/solidity] The developers community often cites Solidity requiring much of third party interfaces and APIs, and its inability to create critical information intensive smart contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO had an objective to provide a new decentralized business model for organizing both commercial and non-profit enterprises.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] It was instantiated on the Ethereum blockchain and had no conventional management structure or board of directors.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] In June 2016, users exploited a vulnerability in The DAO code to enable them to siphon off one-third of The DAO's funds to a subsidiary account.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The Ethereum community controversially decided to hard-fork the Ethereum blockchain to restore approximately all funds to the original contract.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] This split the Ethereum blockchain into two branches, each with its own cryptocurrency, where the original unforked blockchain continued as Ethereum Classic.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] By September 2016, the value token of The DAO, known by the moniker **DAO**, was delisted from major cryptocurrency exchanges (such as Poloniex and Kraken).
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The open source computer code behind the organization was written principally by Christoph Jentzsch, and released publicly on GitHub, where other contributors added to and modified the code.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Simon Jentzsch, Christoph Jentzsch's brother, was also involved in the venture.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO was launched on 30 April 2016 with a website and a 28-day crowdsale to fund the organization.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The token sale had raised more than US$34 million by 10 May 2016, and more than US$50 million-worth of *Ether* (ETH)—the digital value token of the Ethereum network—by 12 May, and over US$100 million by 15 May 2016.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] On 17 May 2016, the largest investor in the DAO held less than 4% of all DAO tokens and the top 100 holders held just over 46% of all DAO tokens.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The fund's Ether value as of 21 May 2016 was more than US$150 million, from more than 11,000 investors.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] As of May 2016, The DAO had attracted nearly 14% of all Ether tokens issued to date.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] On 28 May 2016 the DAO tokens became tradable on various cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] A paper published in May 2016 noted a number of security vulnerabilities associated with The DAO and recommended that investors in The DAO hold off from directing The DAO to invest in projects until the problems had been resolved.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] An Ethereum developer on GitHub pointed out a flaw relating to "recursive calls".
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] On June 9 it was blogged about by Peter Vessenes, founder of the Blockchain Foundation.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] By June 14, fixes had been proposed and were awaiting approval by members of The DAO.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] On June 16, further attention was called to recursive call vulnerabilities by bloggers affiliated with the Initiative for CryptoCurrencies & Contracts (IC3).
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The funds were moved into an account subject to a 28-day holding period under the terms of the Ethereum smart contract so were not actually gone.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Members of The DAO and the Ethereum community debated what to do next, with some calling the attack unethical but valid, since it did not violate DAO rules as coded, while others called for the Ether to be re-appropriated and/or The DAO to be shut down.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO community manager, Griff Green, organized a volunteer group of coders known as The White Hat Group to recoup the funds in the other 500 wallets before they could also be hacked.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Eventually on July 20, 2016, the Ethereum network was hard forked to move the funds in The DAO to a recovery address where they could be exchanged back to Ethereum by their original owners.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] However, some continued to use the original unforked Ethereum blockchain, now called Ethereum Classic.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] In September 2016, Poloniex de-listed DAO trading pairs, followed by Kraken in December 2016.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO was a decentralized autonomous organization that exists as a set of contracts on the Ethereum blockchain, with no physical address or officials with formal authority.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The theory underlying the DAO was that keeping operational power directly in the hands of owners, not delegated to managers, would ensure that invested funds would be used in the owners' best interests, thus solving the principal–agent problem.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] As an on-chain organization, The DAO claimed to be completely transparent, since everything was done by the code which anyone could see and audit.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] However, the complexity of the code base and the rapid deployment of the DAO meant that neither the coders, the auditors, nor the owners could ensure the intended behavior of the organization, with the eventual attacker finding an unexpected loophole.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO was intended to operate as "a hub that disperses funds (currently in Ether, the Ethereum value token) to projects".
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Investors receive voting rights by means of a digital share token; they vote on proposals submitted by *contractors*, and a group of *curator* volunteer make sure the projects are legal and the contractors properly identified before *whitelisting* them.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The profits from an investment will flow back to their stakeholders as specified in an on-chain smart contract.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO did not hold the money of investors; instead, the investors owned DAO tokens that gave them rights to vote on potential projects.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Anyone could pull out their funds by the time they first voted.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO's reliance on Ether allowed people to send their money to it from anywhere in the world without providing any identifying information.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] In May 2016, *TechCrunch* described The DAO as "a paradigm shift in the very idea of economic organization. ...
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The group's logo featured a capital letter Đ.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] In May 2016, the plan called for The DAO to invest Ether into ventures.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] It would back contractors and receive in return "clear payment terms" from contractors.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The organizers promoted The DAO as providing investors with a return on their investment via those "clear payment terms" and they warned investors that there was a "significant risk" that the ventures funded by them may fail.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The risks included unknown attack vectors and programming errors.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Additional risks included the lack of legal precedents: it was unknown how governments and their regulatory agencies would treat The DAO's ventures and contracts.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] For example, legal systems might not acknowledge a corporate veil protecting investors from individual legal and financial liability for actions taken by The DAO and its contractors.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] It was unclear if The DAO was selling securities, which are highly regulated, and if so, what type of securities.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The DAO has a democratized organizational structure so that control can be spread among members, with no official leadership or regulation.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Normally, there is no way to recover funds if a member mistakenly transfers cryptocurrency to the wrong wallet, including in case of fraud.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Additionally, to function in the real world, contractors would likely need to convert the invested Ether into national currencies.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] In May 2016, attorney Andrew Hinkes said that those sales of Ether would likely depress its market value.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] The code behind The DAO had several safeguards against anyone capturing the voting rights of shareholders to win investments.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] However, this would not prevent fraudulent or over-optimistic proposals.
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] A paper cited a "number of security vulnerabilities".
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Slock.it (a German Blockchain venture), and Mobotiq (a French electric vehicle start-up) were listed as seeking potential funding on the daohub.org website during the May "creation period".
[src:smart-contracts/the-dao] Both Jentzsch brothers were involved in Slock.it as well.
